A number of people claim to have [[eidetic memory]], but science has never found a single verifiable case of photographic memory.<ref>http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/i-developed-what-appears-to-be-a-ph/</ref><ref>http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2006/04/kaavya_syndrome.single.html</ref> Eidetic imagery is virtually nonexistent in adults.<ref>http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/180955/eidetic-image</ref> Most people showing amazing memory abilities use [[mnemonic]] strategies, mostly the [[method of loci]]. This includes all winners of the annual [[World Memory Championships]] and most of the known scientific cases of excellent memories, like [[Solomon Shereshevsky]]. Regardless, the following list contains people who have claimed photographic memory.<ref name=vild>Wilding, J.M., & Valentine, E.R.: Superior Memory. Hove, England: Psychology Press (1997).</ref>
==People claimed to possess an eidetic memory== *[[Charles Nalder Baeyertz]], a publisher and music critic in New Zealand. His capacity to memorize a page at a glance enabled him to display an apparently inexhaustible supply of knowledge and to acquire several languages. He claimed to have learnt [[Māori language|Maori]] by memorizing a dictionary. His favourite party trick was to read a newspaper column then recite it backward.<ref>{{cite book | last=Woods | first=Joanna | title=Facing The Music Charles Baeyertz and The Triad | location= | publisher=Otago University Press| year=2008 | isbn=978-1-877372-55-1 }}, pp. 22–23</ref> * [[David Boies]], an American litigator, is frequently described as having a photographic memory that enables him to recite exact text, page numbers, and legal exhibits. Colleagues attribute his courtroom success in part to this ability.<ref>{{cite episode |title=The Information Age |series=The Nineties |network=[[CNN]] |date=2017}}</ref><ref name="Donovan2007">{{cite book|last=Donovan|first=Karen|title=V. Goliath: The Trials of David Boies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zdpnERJeQ1MC&pg=PA81|accessdate=3 September 2017|year=2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-375-72655-2|page=81}}</ref> * Elizabeth, a Harvard student, claimed and disputed.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Charles F Stromeyer III, Eidetikers|title=An Adult Eidetiker|journal=Psychology Today|date=November 1970|pages=76–80|url=http://www.psy.cmu.edu/~kotovsky/85102/readings/old/stromeyer.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Tarek Kerbag|title=Does Photographic Memory Exist?|url=http://www.personal.psu.edu/afr3/blogs/siowfa12/2012/10/does-photographic-memory-exist.html|accessdate=16 December 2015|date=12 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=Foer>{{cite web|author1=Joshua Foer|title=Kaavya Syndrome: No one has a photographic memory|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2006/04/kaavya_syndrome.html|website=slate.com|date=27 April 2006}}</ref> * The mathematician [[Leonhard Euler]] has been characterized as having an eidetic memory.<ref name=Calinger>{{Cite book| last = Calinger | first = Ronald S. | title = Leonhard Euler: Mathematical Genius in the Enlightenment | publisher = Princeton University Press | year = 2015 | page = 22 | isbn = 9780691119274}}</ref> He was able to, for example, repeat the [[Aeneid]] of [[Virgil]] from beginning to end without hesitation, and for every page in the edition he could indicate which line was the first and which was the last even decades after having read it.<ref name=Calinger/> * [[Robert Evans (astronomer)|Robert Evans]] can identify new objects that appear in starfields of 1500 galaxies.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sacks|first1=Oliver|title=An anthropologist on Mars : seven paradoxical tales|date=1995|publisher=Vintage/Picador|location=New York|isbn=0-679-43785-1|edition=1st|page=189}}</ref> * [[Akira Haraguchi]] holds the [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] for the most decimal places of pi recited by memory. His ability is self-attributed to a strong eidetic memory, though he uses a mnemonic device.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adams|first1=Lee|title=The Truth About Photographic Memory|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/articles/200603/the-truth-about-photographic-memory|website=psychologytoday.com|accessdate=16 December 2015|date=1 March 2006}}</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/science/alexs-adventures-in-numberland/2015/mar/13/pi-day-2015-memory-memorisation-world-record-japanese-akira-haraguchi</ref> *The astronomer [[Johannes Kepler]] had a photographic memory according to Rolf Keppler, a descendant of Kepler's brother Christoph.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TP7bFBPSdJQ ''Rolf Keppler in "Ich trage einen großen Namen"''] (minute 6:09) on [[YouTube]]. Rolf Keppler in the German TV show "I have a great name". Retrieved 2017-02-05.</ref> *[[Klaus Kinski]], a German actor, was described by [[Will Tremper]] as having a photographic memory, which allowed him to memorize a book page within minutes.<ref name="Tremper1993">{{cite book|last=Tremper|first=Will|authorlink=Will Tremper|title=Meine wilden Jahre|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qvizAAAAIAAJ&q=%22fotografisches+gedächtnis%22|accessdate=18 February 2017|date=1 January 1993|publisher=Ullstein|isbn=978-3-550-06046-5|page=234}}</ref> *[[Ferdinand Marcos]], the former [[Philippines|Filipino]] [[dictator]]. He claimed to have memorized complicated texts in one glance. He could recite the [[Philippines|Philippine]] 1935 constitution forward and backward. He also passed the [[bar examination]] in 1939 with an almost perfect score at 98.01%. Several people contested his score and a retake was taken, albeit an oral bar examination witnessed by several people.<ref>{{cite book | last=Seagrave | first=Sterling | coauthors= | title=The Marcos Dynasty | location= | publisher=Harpercollins | year=1988 | isbn=0-06-015815-8}}</ref> *[[Said Nursî]], an Ottoman [[Islamic scholar]] who was able to recite many books from memory. For instance "... So then he [Molla Fethullah] decided to test his memory and handed him a copy of the work by [[Al-Hariri of Basra]] (1054–1122) — also famous for his intelligence and power of memory — called ''Maqamat al-Hariri''. Said read one page once, memorized it, then repeated it by heart. Molla Fethullah expressed his amazement."<ref>Şükran Vahide. (2005). ''Islam in Modern Turkey''. State University of New York Press, {{ISBN|0-7914-6515-2}}</ref> *[[Kim Peek]], prodigious savant and inspiration for the character Raymond Babbit, played by [[Dustin Hoffman]] in the film ''[[Rain Man]]''.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article6965115.ece Kim Peek: savant who was the inspiration for the film Rain Man]</ref> * [[Shas Pollak]]s, Jewish mnemonists who memorized the exact layout of words in more than 5,422 pages of the 12 books of the standard edition of the [[Babylonian Talmud]]. However, the claim to eidetic memory was later disputed.<ref name=Foer /> *[[Abubakar Shekau]], the leader of the Nigerian [[Islamist]] militant group [[Boko Haram]], has been described as possessing a photographic memory.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18020349 | work=BBC News | title=Nigeria's Boko Haram leader Abubakar Shekau in profile| date=9 May 2014}}</ref> *[[Sukarno]], the father of Indonesian independence and the first president of the Republic of [[Indonesia]], is said to have had a photographic memory, which helped him in his language learning.<ref>Ludwig M., Arnold (2004). ''King of the Mountain: The Nature of Political Leadership''. University Press of Kentucky. [https://books.google.com/books?id=WWCZuYw_0dIC&pg=PA150&dq=Sukarno%2Bprecocious&as_brr=3&ei=M_W0SZPVDYLeyATPtvXyCg&hl=fr#PPA150,M1 p. 150].</ref> * [[Nikola Tesla]] also is claimed to have possessed photographic memory.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Borowski|first1=Susan|title=The brilliant and tortured world of Nikola Tesla|url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/blogs/scientia/brilliant-and-tortured-world-nikola-tesla|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS) MemberCentral|accessdate=16 December 2015|date=29 May 2012}}</ref> *[[Arturo Toscanini]], an Italian conductor. It was estimated that by the end of his career he had memorized over 200 symphonies and up to 100 operas.<ref>[http://www.bpbclassics.demon.co.uk/toscanini.html "Arturo Tosanini"]. ''bpbclassics.demon.co.uk''. Retrieved 2017-02-06.</ref> "One of his second grade school teachers, Signora Vernoni, noticed that Toscanini could memorize poems after a single reading and could pick out on the piano the songs and arias he had heard people singing."<ref>[http://www.arturotoscanini.org/page2/page2.html "Toscanini: A Brief Biography"]. ''arturotoscanini.org''. Retrieved 2017-02-06.</ref> * [[Leonardo da Vinci]] is said to have possessed photographic memory.<ref name="Rajamanickam2007">{{cite book|author=M. Rajamanickam|title=Modern General Psychology, Second Edition (revised And Expanded) (in 2 Vols.)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eJfXkj56H0kC&pg=PA434|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|isbn=978-81-8069-421-9|pages=434}}</ref> * [[Swami Vivekananda]] is believed to have eidetic memory as he could memorize a book just by going through it for a single time.<ref name="Rangachari2011">{{cite book|last=Rangachari|first=Devika|title=Swami Vivekananda: A Man with a Vision|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ia0CSSnDwUkC&pg=PT21|accessdate=14 January 2016|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-81-8475-563-3|page=21}}</ref> * The mathematician [[John von Neumann]] was able to memorize a column of the phone book at a single glance.<ref name=halmos>{{Cite journal | last = Halmos | first = Paul |date=April 1973 | title = The Legend of von Neumann | journal = [[American Mathematical Monthly]] | volume = 80 | issue = 4 | pages = 382–394 | doi=10.2307/2319080}}</ref> [[Herman Goldstine]] wrote about him: "One of his remarkable abilities was his power of absolute recall. As far as I could tell, von Neumann was able on once reading a book or article to quote it back verbatim; moreover, he could do it years later without hesitation."<ref>''The Computer from Pascal to von Neumann'', by [[Herman Goldstine]], 1972, Princeton Univ. Press, {{ISBN|0-691-08104-2}}, p. 167</ref> *[[Stephen Wiltshire]] is a [[prodigious savant]],<ref>{{cite book | last=Treffert | first=Darold | coauthors= | title=Extraordinary People: understanding "idiot savants" | location=New York | publisher=Harper & Row | year=1989 | isbn=0-06-015945-6}}</ref> capable of drawing the entire skyline of a city after a helicopter ride.<ref>David Martin. ''Savants: Charting "islands of genius"'', [[CNN]] [http://www.cnn.com/2006/HEALTH/09/06/savant.genius/index.html broadcast September 14, 2006]</ref>
